In this example, we use a simple `for` loop to iterate over each element in the slice of floating point numbers (`&mut [f32]`). We then check whether the current index modulo four equals one, two, three, or zero. Based on this result, we perform the corresponding operation on the element at the given index. The first condition corresponds to performing a multiplication by two, while the second condition involves dividing the element by five and checking its new value against a range of allowed values (-1.0 <= x <= 1.0). If the new value falls outside of this range, we panic! This ensures that invalid data cannot pass through our transformation pipeline without being caught early on. Finally, after both steps 1 and 2 have been applied to all elements in the dataset, we move onto step 3, which consists of adding eight to each element. Again, we use a modulo operator to ensure that we only apply this operation once per iteration of the loop.

